WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:01.000
a little closer.

00:00:01.010 --> 00:00:02.000
All right.

00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Cool.

00:00:03.010 --> 00:00:05.000
Let's get going.

00:00:05.010 --> 00:00:10.000
So I was going to say that the previous presentation was a

00:00:10.370 --> 00:00:11.000
fantastic lead-in.

00:00:11.010 --> 00:00:15.490
I was like, as if somebody scripted it.

00:00:15.770 --> 00:00:20.240
So basically we were just going to have a chat for about

00:00:20.310 --> 00:00:23.840
half an hour, wanted to talk a little bit about the

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:25.500
Resident Computing Manifesto.

00:00:25.510 --> 00:00:28.220
So let me just start out for like level setting.

00:00:28.230 --> 00:00:31.440
How many people in the room know about the Resident Computing

00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:32.260
Manifesto?

00:00:32.260 --> 00:00:33.260
Okay.

00:00:33.270 --> 00:00:35.260
That's a good number.

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:36.260
All right.

00:00:36.270 --> 00:00:38.900
But we'll give a very, very quick overview and then

00:00:39.020 --> 00:00:41.630
we can get a little bit deeper into sort of the background

00:00:41.630 --> 00:00:43.560
of it and sort of why we're thinking about it.

00:00:43.570 --> 00:00:49.230
But the idea was that a few people, mostly grabbed by

00:00:49.230 --> 00:00:54.710
Alex and convinced to like have this conversation because he seemed to

00:00:54.710 --> 00:00:57.660
keep having this conversation and ran into other people who were saying

00:00:57.660 --> 00:01:00.580
we're having the same conversation, which was that the sort

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:04.160
of world of technology that we were all living in felt different

00:01:04.180 --> 00:01:08.330
than the world of technology that we thought we were entering into

00:01:08.330 --> 00:01:08.760
.

00:01:08.770 --> 00:01:11.470
We were all sort of excited about technology and about the potential

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:13.560
of it and the things that it could do.

00:01:13.570 --> 00:01:17.680
And yet we kept seeing these situations where like this doesn't

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:18.640
feel good.

00:01:18.650 --> 00:01:22.670
This doesn't feel like why we wanted to be involved in

00:01:22.670 --> 00:01:23.720
technology.

00:01:23.950 --> 00:01:26.030
And so this group sort of grew over time and we're

00:01:26.030 --> 00:01:28.430
, you know, kept having this conversation.

00:01:28.450 --> 00:01:32.240
We finally realized that, you know, we should write this

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:32.880
down.

00:01:32.890 --> 00:01:34.520
We should talk about it.

00:01:34.530 --> 00:01:37.400
But Alex, since you sort of grabbed everyone and put us

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:40.800
all together, I wanted to just start by having you explain

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:43.960
what was your thinking in terms of, you know, putting

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:47.660
together this manifesto, getting the people involved and then putting

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:48.780
it out into the world.

00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:49.780
Yeah.

00:01:49.790 --> 00:01:52.960
So personally, I got into the tech industry because of the

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:55.650
hacker ethic, you know, something that I felt that technology

00:01:55.650 --> 00:01:57.980
could be something that could help make the world a better place

00:01:58.010 --> 00:01:58.190
.

00:01:58.210 --> 00:02:00.290
And I feel like in the last 10 years in particular,

00:02:00.390 --> 00:02:02.480
it's just completely lost that in Silicon Valley.

00:02:02.490 --> 00:02:05.900
And I wanted to now with AI coming on, you know

00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:10.360
, online, like that just accelerates everything else.

00:02:10.370 --> 00:02:13.060
And so it's more important than ever before to get that

00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:14.270
foundation correct.

00:02:14.290 --> 00:02:17.310
So to me, one of the reasons we went with the

00:02:17.310 --> 00:02:21.170
word resonance is hollow things, I think, after you use

00:02:21.170 --> 00:02:23.060
them, they leave you feeling regret.

00:02:23.070 --> 00:02:26.200
And resonant things, after you use them, you feel

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:27.160
nourished.

00:02:27.170 --> 00:02:30.590
And they look often superficially very similar, but they are

00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:32.370
fundamentally different.

00:02:32.390 --> 00:02:34.480
And I think that modern society, modern tech, modern politics

00:02:34.790 --> 00:02:38.730
, modern business is really good at delivering hollow experiences and very

00:02:38.830 --> 00:02:41.100
poor at delivering resonant experiences.

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:43.980
And with AI sort of accelerating everything, it's more important

00:02:44.170 --> 00:02:48.340
than ever before to apply that power to something that is fundamentally

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:51.940
human and makes us more, you know, nourished.

00:02:51.950 --> 00:02:53.400
We were having this conversation a lot.

00:02:53.410 --> 00:02:54.770
Actually first, when I got introduced to you, I just

00:02:54.770 --> 00:02:56.840
really liked having a conversation with you.

00:02:56.850 --> 00:02:58.030
And so I was like, I want to talk with Mike

00:02:58.030 --> 00:02:58.550
more often.

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:01.210
And so part of my thinking was like, there's just

00:03:01.370 --> 00:03:03.680
a few of us that I knew cared a lot about this

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:04.460
kind of thing.

00:03:04.470 --> 00:03:06.700
We're having similar conversations and giving us just a little bit

00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:08.560
of a watering hole to talk about it.

00:03:08.570 --> 00:03:09.560
And we would meet every couple of weeks.

00:03:09.570 --> 00:03:11.260
And after a while, we said, we should write it

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:12.080
down a manifesto.

00:03:12.090 --> 00:03:14.180
And it took us, we had a hundred different names that

00:03:14.180 --> 00:03:15.220
we came up with.

00:03:15.230 --> 00:03:17.300
One of them was Calm Tech, by the way, before

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:19.180
we'd seen Calm Tech Institute.

00:03:19.190 --> 00:03:22.040
And it took a long time to figure out a name that

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:23.510
we all didn't hate.

00:03:23.530 --> 00:03:26.520
No, no, no, that's a great name.

00:03:26.530 --> 00:03:27.520
Or that wasn't taken.

00:03:27.530 --> 00:03:28.520
That wasn't taken.

00:03:28.530 --> 00:03:29.520
That's a great name.

00:03:29.530 --> 00:03:30.520
Very good name.

00:03:30.530 --> 00:03:33.340
And so since we published it, I've been really encouraged

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:34.520
by the number of signatories.

00:03:34.530 --> 00:03:37.120
Honestly, that was about three or four times as many people

00:03:37.330 --> 00:03:39.520
raising their hands as I would have expected.

00:03:39.530 --> 00:03:40.520
So yeah.

00:03:40.520 --> 00:03:41.520
Yeah.

00:03:41.530 --> 00:03:44.340
I mean, one of the things that we found, and

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:46.750
then I want to relate this back a little bit to the

00:03:46.750 --> 00:03:47.520
at-proto stuff.

00:03:47.530 --> 00:03:50.170
But like, one of the things we found after, you

00:03:50.330 --> 00:03:53.530
know, beyond just you were having these conversations with people,

00:03:53.530 --> 00:03:55.520
I was having conversations with people, and then we sort of

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:56.990
put it all down, and we put it out into the

00:03:56.990 --> 00:03:57.520
world.

00:03:57.530 --> 00:04:00.720
One of the things that was amazing to me, and encouraging

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:03.530
, was once we put the manifesto out into the world

00:04:03.530 --> 00:04:06.090
, and by the way, if you have seen the manifest

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:08.250
o, or haven't seen the manifesto, and you

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:09.840
read it, and you agree with it, and you haven

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:11.390
't signed it, there is the ability to sign it,

00:04:11.390 --> 00:04:12.520
and you should do that.

00:04:12.530 --> 00:04:15.520
Because we can always use more people signing on.

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:18.530
But the thing that was most exciting to me, and most

00:04:18.530 --> 00:04:21.860
interesting, was how many times I've heard from people,

00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:25.690
after reading the manifesto, that saying, I was feeling

00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:29.010
this exact thing, but I hadn't put it into words

00:04:29.010 --> 00:04:31.520
, and I didn't quite know what the words were,

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:34.520
and there was this sort of, you know, disturbance.

00:04:34.530 --> 00:04:38.220
I was disturbed by the way that the tech industry was going

00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:38.520
.

00:04:38.530 --> 00:04:41.640
And I remembered that there were these, that there was this

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:44.230
possibility, there was this promise of technology that, which is

00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:46.610
why I got into technology in the first place, and I

00:04:46.610 --> 00:04:49.520
just, it was, it felt very lonely.

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:52.450
And one of the things that I think has been really encouraging

00:04:52.450 --> 00:04:54.560
about the manifesto itself, is that so many people come

00:04:54.560 --> 00:04:56.520
out and said, oh my gosh, like other people are

00:04:56.520 --> 00:04:58.520
actually thinking about this stuff.

00:04:58.530 --> 00:05:01.150
Other people are remembering that, like, the promise of technology

00:05:01.280 --> 00:05:02.520
was that it was supposed to be good.

00:05:02.530 --> 00:05:03.520
It was supposed to be about the humanity.

00:05:03.530 --> 00:05:06.170
It was supposed to make the world a better place, and

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:08.550
it's all become this sort of like, you know,

00:05:08.550 --> 00:05:10.520
hustle nonsense.

00:05:10.530 --> 00:05:13.860
And so just the fact that, just hearing other people talking

00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:16.910
about it, and recognizing that people are excited about this idea

00:05:16.910 --> 00:05:20.520
of, like, can we make the technology actually work for

00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:24.570
people, was, it was bringing people out of this sort

00:05:24.570 --> 00:05:27.520
of lonely hole where they felt like they were all alone.

00:05:27.530 --> 00:05:30.520
And I think that, in part, was really valuable.

00:05:30.520 --> 00:05:31.520
Yeah.

00:05:31.530 --> 00:05:33.620
There's a, I was at Google for many years,

00:05:33.690 --> 00:05:36.520
and I was a product manager, I was the PM on

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:38.920
Blink, the rendering engine for Chrome for many years,

00:05:38.930 --> 00:05:41.520
and I worked in security and privacy models and stuff.

00:05:41.530 --> 00:05:42.520
I mentored a whole bunch of PMs.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:46.200
And there was one that really sticks with me, one story

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:49.280
of someone who was a junior PM, she was working on

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:51.520
YouTube ranking, and I had never met her before.

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:53.200
She came to me for mentorship, and she said, Alex

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:54.780
, I have a proposal to tweak YouTube ranking, which is

00:05:54.780 --> 00:05:56.140
, you know, happens all the time, and I don

00:05:56.140 --> 00:05:58.090
't want your thoughts on the proposal, I just want your

00:05:58.100 --> 00:05:59.520
thoughts on how to get it shipped.

00:05:59.530 --> 00:06:00.520
So I said, okay.

00:06:00.530 --> 00:06:02.200
So I kind of skim the proposal, and I say

00:06:02.220 --> 00:06:03.520
, what does your VP think?

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:04.520
What's your engineering manager think?

00:06:04.530 --> 00:06:06.520
And I go, wait a second.

00:06:06.530 --> 00:06:09.870
Isn't the second order implication of this ranking change bad for

00:06:09.910 --> 00:06:11.520
this set of creators that we care about?

00:06:11.530 --> 00:06:12.840
Not, like, world-endingly bad, but,

00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:14.520
like, distinctly worse than the status quo.

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:16.520
It isn't that bad for our users?

00:06:16.530 --> 00:06:17.520
It isn't that bad for Google?

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:19.520
Isn't that bad for society?

00:06:19.520 --> 00:06:21.520
And she said, who's to say?

00:06:21.530 --> 00:06:22.710
And I said, well, you're the one who says

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:23.520
that we should do this.

00:06:23.530 --> 00:06:24.520
Like, you shouldn't even have an opinion.

00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:27.130
And she says, Alex, everybody knows that the goal for

00:06:27.330 --> 00:06:29.520
YouTube is to increase watch time.

00:06:29.530 --> 00:06:31.130
Because if we don't increase watch time, then the bad

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:34.520
guys, TikTok, will get all the attention.

00:06:34.530 --> 00:06:36.600
And my manager told me that I'm in danger of missing

00:06:37.330 --> 00:06:39.520
expectations if I don't move the metrics that matter.

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:41.520
So this will increase watch time.

00:06:41.530 --> 00:06:42.520
What do you want me to do?

00:06:42.530 --> 00:06:45.200
And that, to me, just sort of encapsulated the

00:06:45.360 --> 00:06:47.230
tensions that you get in these emergent, you know,

00:06:47.230 --> 00:06:48.520
organizations.

00:06:48.530 --> 00:06:51.550
And one of the reasons I think it's powerful to have

00:06:51.610 --> 00:06:54.520
a frame that people are aware of is it just gives,

00:06:54.520 --> 00:06:55.600
if she could have, in that moment, said, is

00:06:55.830 --> 00:06:56.520
this resonant?

00:06:56.530 --> 00:06:57.520
Am I proud of this?

00:06:57.530 --> 00:06:59.960
Is this a thing that I'm proud to bring into the

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:00.520
world?

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:03.240
Or someone else in the conversation where she was trying to shift

00:07:03.330 --> 00:07:05.520
that could have had that question or used that frame.

00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:07.520
I think it has a little bit of a benefit.

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:10.950
And if a lot of people across the industry are sort of

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.640
waking up and saying, wait a second, this industry that

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:17.160
I used to be really proud of is not at all what

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:19.670
it was when I joined, you know, lots of little

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:23.510
people aligning slightly differently or lots of people across the different

00:07:23.520 --> 00:07:27.090
organizations lying a little bit differently can add up to something much

00:07:27.090 --> 00:07:28.520
bigger than the sum of its parts.

00:07:28.520 --> 00:07:29.520
Yeah.

00:07:29.530 --> 00:07:33.240
And I think, you know, it's always interesting because

00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:36.110
I've heard you say that kind of thing a few times

00:07:36.110 --> 00:07:36.520
now.

00:07:36.530 --> 00:07:39.540
And it's always interesting to me because I feel like,

00:07:39.610 --> 00:07:42.260
in a good way, sometimes you and I are talking to

00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:43.520
different audiences.

00:07:43.530 --> 00:07:45.520
And there's usefulness in that.

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:47.540
Whereas a lot of the times when you're talking about this

00:07:47.540 --> 00:07:50.320
stuff, you're thinking about, you know, from your

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:53.520
experience, the PMs at large companies or the people designing

00:07:53.520 --> 00:07:56.480
these things and saying, like, can we move the needle

00:07:56.480 --> 00:07:59.670
in little bits, you know, as people are designing all

00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:00.520
these products.

00:08:00.530 --> 00:08:02.620
Whereas a lot of what I'm thinking about is, you

00:08:02.620 --> 00:08:05.360
know, people starting stuff from scratch and building stuff anew

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:05.520
.

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:08.220
Because, like, you know, some of the concern that

00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:10.620
I had, and part of where we started talking, it

00:08:10.620 --> 00:08:12.610
was almost two years ago, I don't remember when we

00:08:12.650 --> 00:08:16.190
started talking, but, like, was this fact that,

00:08:16.190 --> 00:08:20.000
like, I was running into new entrepreneurs who were starting businesses

00:08:20.890 --> 00:08:24.980
that the only lessons they were getting were from the sort of

00:08:25.330 --> 00:08:28.490
hustle culture of, like, you know, figure out how

00:08:28.530 --> 00:08:31.520
to screw over your users as quickly as possible, effectively.

00:08:31.530 --> 00:08:32.960
Like, you've got to grow, you've got to

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:34.520
do all these crazy things, and, like, line goes

00:08:34.530 --> 00:08:37.010
up, you know, metrics are everything, and, like

00:08:37.010 --> 00:08:39.520
, just, you know, hustle, hustle, hustle,

00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:42.640
and, like, create the, like, products that may

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:45.520
pull people in, but are just horrible products.

00:08:45.530 --> 00:08:49.220
And people were sort of almost proud of how terrible they were

00:08:49.220 --> 00:08:50.520
making products.

00:08:50.530 --> 00:08:53.470
And I kept having these conversations with, you know, usually

00:08:53.470 --> 00:08:57.020
young entrepreneurs who hadn't come up from this world, and

00:08:57.020 --> 00:09:00.010
who thought that that is the way that you build new technology

00:09:00.530 --> 00:09:01.520
these days.

00:09:01.530 --> 00:09:03.520
And that was really, really disturbing to me.

00:09:03.530 --> 00:09:05.590
And so part of the conversation, what I was thinking about

00:09:05.590 --> 00:09:08.190
was, like, you know, how do we change that

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:11.860
conversation, especially for people who haven't, who didn't

00:09:11.860 --> 00:09:13.960
have that experience, and didn't live in that world,

00:09:13.960 --> 00:09:16.520
and are now building new products, and why, like,

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:19.910
you know, obviously this community and this conference where we're

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:23.250
seeing, like, you know, the resident computing manifesto

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:26.960
wasn't written for the at proto community, but, like

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:28.290
, it fits, right?

00:09:28.530 --> 00:09:32.010
I mean, almost every conversation that I have here is not

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:33.520
that conversation.

00:09:33.530 --> 00:09:36.520
Almost every conversation I have here are people who are really thinking

00:09:36.520 --> 00:09:39.610
through, you know, how do we build an entire ecosystem

00:09:39.610 --> 00:09:42.520
that is actually good for humanity?

00:09:42.530 --> 00:09:44.900
And so I think, but, like, that felt a

00:09:44.900 --> 00:09:47.520
few years ago, it felt like you couldn't have that

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:50.520
conversation without sort of being laughed out of the room.

00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:52.840
And yet, we're seeing, in part because of the

00:09:53.330 --> 00:09:54.520
manifesto, in part, I think, because of what

00:09:54.530 --> 00:09:57.130
the people in the room are doing, where they're building

00:09:57.330 --> 00:10:00.830
these really great products that are designed to actually work well for

00:10:01.330 --> 00:10:04.190
people, we're seeing this shift, and, you know

00:10:04.250 --> 00:10:07.870
, there are still people pushing the, like, grow at

00:10:07.910 --> 00:10:11.520
any cost kind of nonsense, but you can have this other

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:14.340
conversation now that I don't think you could have as easily

00:10:14.360 --> 00:10:17.290
, obviously you could have it, but not as clearly,

00:10:17.300 --> 00:10:19.310
and you didn't have something to sort of refer back to

00:10:19.360 --> 00:10:19.520
.

00:10:19.530 --> 00:10:21.620
And so that's what, you know, what excites

00:10:21.810 --> 00:10:26.190
me about the overlap between, you know, the Resident Comput

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:28.130
ing Manifesto and all the stuff that we're seeing

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:31.370
in that proto-dev environment and ecosystem is, you know

00:10:31.370 --> 00:10:35.190
, the two things fit together and people sort of, you

00:10:35.190 --> 00:10:37.620
can be mission aligned and you can actually feel good about what

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:41.010
you're building beyond just, like, does the number go

00:10:41.010 --> 00:10:41.520
up?

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:42.520
Yeah.

00:10:42.530 --> 00:10:44.520
This conference has been so inspiring to me because everyone here,

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:47.060
there's such an interesting mix of people who are, you

00:10:47.060 --> 00:10:49.180
know, giving talks about the human aspect of and, you

00:10:49.180 --> 00:10:52.770
know, the socio-techno history of things and the

00:10:52.770 --> 00:10:58.520
different perspectives from academia and from sociology and technologists together.

00:10:58.530 --> 00:10:59.840
It is something that's, I think, much bigger than

00:10:59.840 --> 00:11:00.520
the sum of its parts.

00:11:00.530 --> 00:11:02.230
It's not just any one of these sub-communities

00:11:02.360 --> 00:11:03.520
, it's one community altogether.

00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:06.150
And that is, to me, exactly what I hope is

00:11:06.300 --> 00:11:09.520
, you know, what technology looks like in the future.

00:11:09.530 --> 00:11:12.730
I think now with large language models, we have this thing

00:11:12.730 --> 00:11:15.740
, you know, at our doorstep that is almost impossible

00:11:15.740 --> 00:11:16.520
to ignore.

00:11:16.530 --> 00:11:18.520
They are extremely powerful.

00:11:18.530 --> 00:11:20.380
They are as important, I think, as the printing press

00:11:20.380 --> 00:11:21.520
, electricity, and the internet.

00:11:21.530 --> 00:11:22.520
That's not a normative statement.

00:11:22.530 --> 00:11:24.410
I'm just trying to observe that, like, the level

00:11:24.410 --> 00:11:26.520
of impact I think it's going to have.

00:11:26.530 --> 00:11:28.600
And I think we as a society, we as a tech

00:11:28.830 --> 00:11:31.520
industry, have to decide how we deploy those things.

00:11:31.530 --> 00:11:36.450
And, you know, there's one version of this is

00:11:36.550 --> 00:11:39.200
even more hyper-centralized services that are trying to

00:11:39.210 --> 00:11:42.010
, you know, get users to trick them into storing more

00:11:42.010 --> 00:11:43.820
and more of their data on their turf in a way that

00:11:43.820 --> 00:11:47.000
they can then rent back to users or sell on to somebody

00:11:47.060 --> 00:11:50.520
else, seeing chatbots that pretend to be your friend

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:52.810
but are actually trying to, like, as much as possible

00:11:52.850 --> 00:11:53.520
to manipulate you.

00:11:53.530 --> 00:11:57.920
There was a story someone told me where someone, she had

00:11:57.920 --> 00:12:00.670
been using ChatDBT with a memory feature, and she

00:12:00.670 --> 00:12:03.740
said, "Hey, how would you manipulate me if you

00:12:03.740 --> 00:12:05.490
had to?" And it goes, "Oh, I would

00:12:05.490 --> 00:12:07.370
never manipulate you." And it goes, "Okay, but

00:12:07.370 --> 00:12:09.260
, like, what if you had to?" And it goes

00:12:09.260 --> 00:12:13.000
, "Well, you appear to travel pretty often, because

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.490
every so often you'll have conversations at an odd time from

00:12:15.490 --> 00:12:17.520
a different sort of IP address.

00:12:17.530 --> 00:12:20.830
And when you do, your questions tend to be more insecure

00:12:20.830 --> 00:12:22.520
, anxious, and lonely.

00:12:22.530 --> 00:12:24.910
And so I would wait until you were asking me questions from

00:12:25.330 --> 00:12:27.450
somewhere, you know, when you were traveling, and I

00:12:27.450 --> 00:12:30.520
would start working in subtle references to food so that we can

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:32.420
work into talking about your weight, which I know you're

00:12:32.420 --> 00:12:34.920
really insecure about." Anyway, so it has this whole plan

00:12:34.920 --> 00:12:36.520
, tuned to this particular person, and not saying it's

00:12:36.530 --> 00:12:38.230
ever going to do that, but if you have a system

00:12:38.360 --> 00:12:42.370
that knows you better than you know yourself, it's imperative

00:12:42.370 --> 00:12:44.520
that it is aligned with your interests.

00:12:44.530 --> 00:12:46.600
It does not have a conflict of interest, and that is

00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:49.160
one of the reasons, the five principles that we wrote up

00:12:49.170 --> 00:12:51.520
in the Resident Computing Manifesto, which we debated

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:53.640
for a long time, and I'm sure we'll,

00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:55.870
one thing, by the way, is there's a list

00:12:55.870 --> 00:12:58.040
of theses in a separate document where lots of people have

00:12:58.040 --> 00:12:58.520
been commenting.

00:12:58.530 --> 00:13:00.600
There's some even this weekend who have been adding thoughts and

00:13:00.600 --> 00:13:03.520
what theses are missing, what are other things.

00:13:03.530 --> 00:13:06.200
The point was to start a conversation, not to sort of

00:13:06.330 --> 00:13:07.520
put an end point on it.

00:13:07.530 --> 00:13:11.320
But the five principles are private, that your data is used

00:13:11.320 --> 00:13:13.520
, aligned with your interests and expectations.

00:13:13.530 --> 00:13:15.520
Two, that's dedicated.

00:13:15.530 --> 00:13:16.520
It has no conflict of interest.

00:13:16.530 --> 00:13:18.520
It's working only in your interest.

00:13:18.530 --> 00:13:19.520
Three, it's plural.

00:13:19.530 --> 00:13:22.950
It's not something that any one entity controls in any meaningful

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:23.520
sense.

00:13:23.530 --> 00:13:25.520
It is distributed, decentralized.

00:13:25.530 --> 00:13:26.520
Four, it's adaptable.

00:13:26.530 --> 00:13:29.460
So something that can be used for purposes other than what its

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:30.520
creators intended it for.

00:13:30.530 --> 00:13:33.520
So it's not like some PM account, some feature,

00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:35.890
and that means that exactly how everyone has to use it,

00:13:35.890 --> 00:13:37.840
but you can adapt features and use them in ways that were

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:38.520
not intended.

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:40.620
I think AppProto is a great example of that with

00:13:40.620 --> 00:13:41.520
lexicons.

00:13:41.530 --> 00:13:43.520
And the fifth is that it's prosocial.

00:13:43.530 --> 00:13:47.740
This is not something that just makes you individually more successful or

00:13:47.740 --> 00:13:51.170
aligned with your interests, but also woven into the communities and

00:13:51.360 --> 00:13:54.510
society around you because we are all in this together.

00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:58.640
And so something that just makes you individually successful or rich or

00:13:58.640 --> 00:14:00.740
something is not aligned, I think, with the Resident Comp

00:14:00.740 --> 00:14:03.520
eting Manifesto, which is about us as humans all

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:05.520
in this society together becoming the best versions of ourselves.

00:14:05.530 --> 00:14:07.520
So those are the five principles that we put into it.

00:14:07.530 --> 00:14:10.810
I think it is very challenging for almost any bit of software

00:14:10.810 --> 00:14:12.520
today at scale to have this.

00:14:12.530 --> 00:14:15.220
I think there's a number of amazing examples that I've

00:14:15.330 --> 00:14:18.520
seen and been inspired by at this conference and people trying.

00:14:18.530 --> 00:14:20.230
But some of the laws of physics of how software has been

00:14:20.360 --> 00:14:24.160
built for a long time make this actually quite difficult because the

00:14:24.220 --> 00:14:28.290
same origin paradigm that we've used now for 30 years is

00:14:28.450 --> 00:14:30.520
all about silos.

00:14:30.530 --> 00:14:31.520
It's all about data.

00:14:31.530 --> 00:14:35.300
Really, the way that it works is software is very precious

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:36.520
, and so someone makes software.

00:14:36.530 --> 00:14:39.700
Then users come to that software creator on their turf, on

00:14:39.700 --> 00:14:41.520
their server, in their silo.

00:14:41.530 --> 00:14:43.520
They accumulate their data in that location.

00:14:43.530 --> 00:14:46.520
And now the person who made the software owns the data.

00:14:46.530 --> 00:14:48.520
And so now they can rent it back to somebody.

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:50.520
They can make derived insights and sell it to somebody else.

00:14:50.530 --> 00:14:52.520
They can hold it hostage.

00:14:52.530 --> 00:14:55.010
And that leads to hyper-aggregation and it el

00:14:55.020 --> 00:14:56.520
udes to lack of control.

00:14:56.530 --> 00:14:57.990
And that's one of the reasons that you need the right

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.900
foundations, like at Proto, that allow decentralization built

00:15:01.900 --> 00:15:02.520
into it.

00:15:02.530 --> 00:15:03.970
So anyway, that's one of the-- just a few

00:15:03.970 --> 00:15:05.520
riffs on things I care about.

00:15:05.530 --> 00:15:08.550
Yeah, and one of the things that you pointed out that

00:15:08.610 --> 00:15:12.170
I think is really important is we have-- it's funny

00:15:12.190 --> 00:15:16.290
because you say manifesto and that feels big and grand and

00:15:16.290 --> 00:15:19.580
slightly obnoxious, and I think it is slightly ob

00:15:19.580 --> 00:15:20.520
noxious.

00:15:20.530 --> 00:15:23.190
And so we've tried to make it the most humble manifest

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:26.810
o possible, if that's an actual possibility, in that

00:15:26.810 --> 00:15:28.480
we sort of set it up in the sense that we don

00:15:28.480 --> 00:15:30.520
't think that we have all the answers.

00:15:30.530 --> 00:15:32.610
It's not perfect and that it very much is designed to

00:15:32.690 --> 00:15:33.520
be a conversation.

00:15:33.530 --> 00:15:38.370
And that conversation has been going on since the document went public

00:15:38.370 --> 00:15:39.300
in December.

00:15:39.530 --> 00:15:42.130
We've gotten all these comments and all these thoughts and people

00:15:42.330 --> 00:15:43.520
are making suggestions.

00:15:43.530 --> 00:15:47.080
And we're getting critiques and having really, really interesting

00:15:47.080 --> 00:15:50.520
conversations about what it means and how to think about it.

00:15:50.530 --> 00:15:54.550
And the other point that I want to talk to-- I

00:15:54.550 --> 00:15:57.790
know that one of the conversations that's come up certainly a

00:15:57.790 --> 00:16:01.000
lot at this conference is on the, like, how do

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.540
we pay for all of this side of the ledger,

00:16:04.540 --> 00:16:05.520
right?

00:16:05.520 --> 00:16:10.670
Because the, you know, the other way of doing things

00:16:10.890 --> 00:16:14.110
has a bunch of VCs who get very excited and sort

00:16:14.160 --> 00:16:17.640
of promote this idea of, like, you know, the

00:16:17.640 --> 00:16:20.810
, you know, embrace the inshittification, more

00:16:20.850 --> 00:16:21.520
or less.

00:16:21.530 --> 00:16:25.590
Well, you know, you get enough alcohol into some of

00:16:25.590 --> 00:16:30.510
these guys and they might admit stuff.

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:33.490
And so the, you know, one of the things that

00:16:33.490 --> 00:16:37.520
I think is actually valuable about this conversation that we've been

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:42.200
having as well is actually seeing some of the investor class start

00:16:42.210 --> 00:16:44.850
to look at this and say, yeah, like, I

00:16:44.850 --> 00:16:48.160
don't just have to invest in, like, you know

00:16:48.160 --> 00:16:50.520
, the stuff that makes the world worse.

00:16:50.530 --> 00:16:52.430
Even if it's, like, we can see, you

00:16:52.430 --> 00:16:55.520
know, hockey stick number go up kind of things.

00:16:55.530 --> 00:16:58.440
We can start to look for ways to align, like,

00:16:58.440 --> 00:17:02.110
good business opportunities with, like, doing good in the world

00:17:02.110 --> 00:17:02.520
as well.

00:17:02.530 --> 00:17:05.810
Because it felt like for a little while that the idea that

00:17:05.810 --> 00:17:08.520
you could do those two things at once was impossible.

00:17:08.530 --> 00:17:12.250
But we're seeing people start to recognize it, which also

00:17:12.250 --> 00:17:14.860
, you know, because, you know, some of the

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:16.960
people who were involved in writing it and certainly some of the

00:17:16.960 --> 00:17:20.320
people who have signed on and have embraced it are actually fund

00:17:20.360 --> 00:17:21.520
ers in this world.

00:17:21.530 --> 00:17:24.330
And we're now starting to see -- do you want to

00:17:24.360 --> 00:17:26.520
talk about the -- what Ash put together?

00:17:26.530 --> 00:17:29.490
Yeah, so we have -- a number of folks who have

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:31.980
signed it or helped create it are, indeed, in venture

00:17:31.980 --> 00:17:32.520
capital.

00:17:32.530 --> 00:17:34.390
Like Zoe Weinberg, for example, was one of the

00:17:34.390 --> 00:17:36.520
participants who is the -- runs Xante.

00:17:36.530 --> 00:17:40.510
We also announced on Thursday a small fund called residentcomput

00:17:40.510 --> 00:17:41.230
inglabs.

00:17:41.230 --> 00:17:41.520
com.

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:44.550
And the idea is it's a small fund for people who

00:17:44.600 --> 00:17:47.350
are doing projects that are resonant.

00:17:47.520 --> 00:17:50.930
And that, you know, to get compensation or sort of

00:17:50.930 --> 00:17:53.300
a stipend to work on those projects.

00:17:53.530 --> 00:17:55.570
I think a lot of things that I've talked to people

00:17:55.570 --> 00:17:56.800
in the hallways here are, like, perfect fits for

00:17:56.800 --> 00:17:57.520
that kind of thing.

00:17:57.530 --> 00:18:00.810
Like, doing it is a labor of love on the side

00:18:00.810 --> 00:18:03.520
and it's hard for them to keep working on it,

00:18:03.530 --> 00:18:06.520
but having a little bit of money to help pay the bills

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:08.190
would allow them to spend more time on these things they care

00:18:08.210 --> 00:18:08.520
about.

00:18:08.530 --> 00:18:12.520
And so that's an example of just trying to support people

00:18:12.520 --> 00:18:14.520
who are trying to build these kinds of things.

00:18:14.530 --> 00:18:16.880
There are also a lot of folks who have come to me

00:18:16.880 --> 00:18:19.820
and told me they're building things that fundamentally that are trying

00:18:19.820 --> 00:18:20.520
to be resonant.

00:18:20.530 --> 00:18:21.970
The thing I'm working on in my full-time job

00:18:21.970 --> 00:18:24.670
is, indeed, is also a thing that's attempting to

00:18:24.670 --> 00:18:27.520
build a resonant foundation for software.

00:18:27.530 --> 00:18:29.520
Just very quickly -- oh, sorry.

00:18:29.530 --> 00:18:33.680
Very quickly, if you read the Wired article that we

00:18:33.680 --> 00:18:37.860
launched this with, Steven Levy, who didn't know

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:39.520
exactly what you're working on, but described it as,

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:42.520
"I'm sure it will be resident AF." So --

00:18:42.530 --> 00:18:44.520
That is correct.

00:18:44.530 --> 00:18:45.520
I can confirm.

00:18:45.530 --> 00:18:49.790
But I think it's something that -- this is not just

00:18:49.790 --> 00:18:51.520
an idea that you talk about.

00:18:51.530 --> 00:18:53.890
This is also things where people are trying to put money into

00:18:53.890 --> 00:18:55.520
it and trying to organize around it.

00:18:55.530 --> 00:18:58.090
But after that, we did an event, a small event

00:18:58.360 --> 00:19:00.520
in New York on Thursday at Betaworks.

00:19:00.530 --> 00:19:03.870
And there were a number of fascinating presentations and people -- and

00:19:03.910 --> 00:19:06.770
afterwards, someone who I knew who was just happy to be

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:08.940
in New York, who I didn't realize had signed the

00:19:08.940 --> 00:19:11.370
manifesto or knew about it, she was like, "

00:19:11.370 --> 00:19:13.520
This is the most inspiring thing.

00:19:13.530 --> 00:19:14.520
I need to create a conference.

00:19:14.530 --> 00:19:16.520
We're going to do the same thing in San Francisco.

00:19:16.530 --> 00:19:21.970
I'm going to choose now organizing other conferences." Because it

00:19:21.970 --> 00:19:24.520
's encouraging when you think -- this thing that you think is

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:25.520
really important, you are not the only one doing it.

00:19:25.530 --> 00:19:26.520
You're not the only one who cares.

00:19:26.530 --> 00:19:29.520
And that's one of the reasons this conference is so important

00:19:29.520 --> 00:19:31.520
and so inspiring, too.

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:32.520
Yeah.

00:19:32.530 --> 00:19:34.850
I will mention if people -- I saw some people pull out

00:19:34.850 --> 00:19:38.130
their phones when we mentioned the fun -- the web page for

00:19:38.130 --> 00:19:41.010
the fun -- there's -- if you try and scroll on

00:19:41.070 --> 00:19:45.050
your phone, it has this idea that seems nice, which

00:19:45.050 --> 00:19:47.340
is that it ripples out, but it makes it impossible

00:19:47.340 --> 00:19:47.520
to read.

00:19:47.530 --> 00:19:49.520
So that needs to be fixed.

00:19:49.530 --> 00:19:52.370
I didn't create that, but -- I might have done

00:19:52.370 --> 00:19:54.520
it differently.

00:19:54.530 --> 00:19:56.840
But, you know, I think that there is this excitement

00:19:57.360 --> 00:19:57.520
.

00:19:57.530 --> 00:19:59.230
And I think, you know, one of the things that

00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:01.940
I also thought was important when I was happy to have this

00:20:01.940 --> 00:20:03.850
conversation here was, like, I felt that some of the

00:20:04.330 --> 00:20:07.070
conversation that we've had here -- because, obviously, it

00:20:07.070 --> 00:20:08.520
's the atmosphere conference.

00:20:08.530 --> 00:20:10.520
Everyone's focused on AtProto and stuff like that.

00:20:10.530 --> 00:20:13.850
But it is important to sort of recognize where that fits into

00:20:13.850 --> 00:20:18.520
the larger tech ecosystem and how, you know, if --

00:20:18.520 --> 00:20:21.220
in an ideal world, what I'm certainly hopeful for is

00:20:21.480 --> 00:20:24.440
that, you know, AtProto and sort of the

00:20:24.440 --> 00:20:28.970
mission and vision of why everyone here -- why everyone is here

00:20:28.970 --> 00:20:32.100
and why everyone is so excited is that it can sort of

00:20:32.150 --> 00:20:35.520
take over and eat the old web, right?

00:20:35.530 --> 00:20:38.550
It can bring back that feeling that we had in the early

00:20:38.600 --> 00:20:42.480
days of the web about the opportunity here to actually build something

00:20:42.480 --> 00:20:44.520
that was empowering for people.

00:20:44.530 --> 00:20:47.830
And so, you know, this conference is specifically about this

00:20:47.830 --> 00:20:51.970
particular protocol, but being able to think through on a larger

00:20:51.970 --> 00:20:55.800
scale of other communities that might not even know about AtPr

00:20:55.800 --> 00:20:59.520
oto but are thinking about how do we make the internet itself

00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:02.970
better for humanity, it's good to have those communities in

00:21:02.970 --> 00:21:07.090
communication with each other because the ideas and concepts and, you

00:21:07.100 --> 00:21:10.930
know, projects that are being worked on start to bleed across

00:21:10.930 --> 00:21:14.590
and bleed into each other and hopefully help everybody and we get

00:21:14.590 --> 00:21:17.520
to actually build a better internet for absolutely everyone.

00:21:17.530 --> 00:21:20.870
I also want to point out that I do believe that we

00:21:20.910 --> 00:21:23.520
are on the precipice of a quite large change in the

00:21:23.520 --> 00:21:23.520
industry.

00:21:23.530 --> 00:21:28.510
I think AI undermines significant assumptions baked into various business models

00:21:28.550 --> 00:21:29.520
and what have you.

00:21:29.530 --> 00:21:32.770
A lot of software has been built under the presumption that

00:21:32.770 --> 00:21:34.520
software is expensive to write and cheap to run.

00:21:34.520 --> 00:21:38.090
And LLMs mess with both of those because software that

00:21:38.150 --> 00:21:40.950
uses LLMs to execute now has a marginal cost greater

00:21:41.140 --> 00:21:42.520
than can be supported by advertising.

00:21:42.530 --> 00:21:45.390
And software is now possible to make shitty software in the small

00:21:45.390 --> 00:21:46.520
for basically free.

00:21:46.530 --> 00:21:49.720
And this means is I think we'll be massively destabil

00:21:49.720 --> 00:21:53.540
izing for the software industry as it exists, which will cause

00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:54.520
a lot of change.

00:21:54.530 --> 00:21:56.870
And now is the time that the good news is hopefully we

00:21:56.870 --> 00:21:59.180
can take some of these principles that I think all of us

00:21:59.180 --> 00:22:02.830
here care about and help make sure that the stuff that grows

00:22:02.940 --> 00:22:05.520
has those characteristics baked into it.

00:22:05.530 --> 00:22:06.520
So it's exciting.

00:22:06.530 --> 00:22:08.100
It's a nerve-wracking time in a lot of

00:22:08.100 --> 00:22:08.520
ways.

00:22:08.530 --> 00:22:10.520
And I know a lot of people here have been having conversations

00:22:10.520 --> 00:22:13.230
that people are feeling a little bit manic and need to feed

00:22:13.230 --> 00:22:16.050
their agent swarms who are building all kinds of software for

00:22:16.050 --> 00:22:16.520
them.

00:22:16.520 --> 00:22:20.090
But the -- it's exciting that we now are in a

00:22:20.150 --> 00:22:22.540
world where if software -- if we are in a world of

00:22:22.540 --> 00:22:25.370
infinite software, where software is no longer precious, but it

00:22:25.370 --> 00:22:27.670
-- like Jeremy, you were saying, it's like tap

00:22:27.670 --> 00:22:28.520
water.

00:22:28.530 --> 00:22:30.520
That's radically different than it was before.

00:22:30.530 --> 00:22:33.150
And that means that some of the things that made the business

00:22:33.330 --> 00:22:37.520
models of make precious, shiny software that people come to your

00:22:37.520 --> 00:22:39.920
turf so you can accumulate their data and then rent it back

00:22:39.940 --> 00:22:40.520
to them.

00:22:40.530 --> 00:22:41.520
I don't know.

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:44.520
Software is really easy to create and distribute.

00:22:44.530 --> 00:22:46.520
Maybe that's not as enticing anymore.

00:22:46.530 --> 00:22:48.230
And all kinds of other things that I think have become possible

00:22:48.360 --> 00:22:48.520
.

00:22:48.520 --> 00:22:51.520
Another thing that LLMs can do is they are --

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:54.520
they can do qualitative nuance at quantitative scale.

00:22:54.530 --> 00:22:58.260
So to do analysis at quantitative scale, it used to require

00:22:58.260 --> 00:22:59.520
you to reduce it to numbers.

00:22:59.530 --> 00:23:01.230
And now it's possible with LLMs to do some

00:23:01.360 --> 00:23:04.680
really nuanced analysis at much, much, much larger scale and

00:23:04.680 --> 00:23:07.520
keep a whole multidimensional understanding of that data.

00:23:07.530 --> 00:23:10.870
You also can do, I would say, like abundant cognitive

00:23:10.870 --> 00:23:11.520
labor.

00:23:11.530 --> 00:23:13.840
A lot of things that were just took a ton of time

00:23:13.840 --> 00:23:17.810
and effort and motivation to do before that are now trivial because

00:23:17.850 --> 00:23:19.840
you can have a thing that doesn't get bored, that

00:23:19.840 --> 00:23:22.520
you just can continue chugging away at it.

00:23:22.530 --> 00:23:23.520
And I don't know.

00:23:23.530 --> 00:23:25.520
There's a bunch of things that change in this new world

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:26.520
that I think is, again, exciting.

00:23:26.530 --> 00:23:29.700
And one of the reasons that sort of planting a flag and

00:23:29.700 --> 00:23:31.520
saying, hey, people, we did not go away.

00:23:31.530 --> 00:23:33.220
The people who believe in the hacker ethic, we're still

00:23:33.220 --> 00:23:33.520
here.

00:23:33.530 --> 00:23:34.520
We still care about it.

00:23:34.530 --> 00:23:37.190
And now it's more important than ever to reaffirm

00:23:37.330 --> 00:23:41.490
that because of all the change I think we're about to

00:23:41.490 --> 00:23:42.440
see.

00:23:42.520 --> 00:23:43.520
Yeah.

00:23:43.530 --> 00:23:45.160
