00:27:31.530 --> 00:27:34.110
One word that wasn't in this discussion, at least I

00:27:34.330 --> 00:27:36.520
didn't hear, is, like, capitalism.

00:27:36.530 --> 00:27:38.840
And how much of all of what we're seeing in tech

00:27:38.840 --> 00:27:40.520
today is just downstream.

00:27:40.530 --> 00:27:42.520
It's capitalism doing business as usual.

00:27:42.530 --> 00:27:45.420
And are new alternatives going to be some kind of post-

00:27:45.420 --> 00:27:46.520
capitalist future?

00:27:46.530 --> 00:27:47.520
Or can they live together?

00:27:47.530 --> 00:27:49.610
Can it be capitalism where VCs suddenly change their minds and

00:27:50.330 --> 00:27:51.520
decide they want to be pro-social?

00:27:51.530 --> 00:27:53.520
Like, what are you envisioning?

00:27:53.530 --> 00:27:55.890
That's a great question to have after we're already out

00:27:55.890 --> 00:27:56.520
over time.

00:27:56.530 --> 00:27:59.520
Because the answer to that is really long and really involved.

00:27:59.530 --> 00:28:01.710
And I've been, like, trying to work on a

00:28:01.710 --> 00:28:04.860
giant paper, which possibly might turn into a book, just

00:28:04.860 --> 00:28:07.520
to answer that question, kind of.

00:28:07.530 --> 00:28:12.500
The short version is that -- well, there is no short

00:28:12.550 --> 00:28:13.300
version.

00:28:13.530 --> 00:28:17.520
That is the question that goes to the heart of this.

00:28:17.530 --> 00:28:19.520
How many of these things go back to different things?

00:28:19.530 --> 00:28:21.840
I do think that there is a world in which the incentive

00:28:22.360 --> 00:28:25.520
structure of capitalism does work towards a resonant future.

00:28:25.530 --> 00:28:27.520
But you have to be very conscious about it.

00:28:27.530 --> 00:28:28.520
You have to think about it.

00:28:28.530 --> 00:28:30.520
And you also have to have a long time horizon.

00:28:30.530 --> 00:28:33.550
There's a lot in there that I think is time horizon

00:28:33.600 --> 00:28:34.520
dependent.

00:28:34.530 --> 00:28:36.520
And then you have to deal with that factor.

00:28:36.530 --> 00:28:38.840
And I think a lot of the problems that we come across

00:28:39.050 --> 00:28:41.940
right now are the fact that everybody is sort of focused on

00:28:41.940 --> 00:28:44.440
a three-month to one-year time horizon.

00:28:44.530 --> 00:28:45.520
You can change that.

00:28:45.520 --> 00:28:49.320
And there are things structurally that we can do that keep

00:28:49.320 --> 00:28:54.080
the sort of incentive structure of free market to incentivize people

00:28:54.080 --> 00:28:57.200
to experiment and do different things and build cool things that find

00:28:57.200 --> 00:28:58.520
value in the world.

00:28:58.530 --> 00:29:00.520
And something that is actually good for humanity.

00:29:00.530 --> 00:29:02.520
But there are some other structural changes.

00:29:02.520 --> 00:29:04.520
There's a lot more.

00:29:04.530 --> 00:29:07.520
But really quickly because we're definitely over time.

00:29:07.530 --> 00:29:10.550
But Eric Reese has a new book coming out relatively soon that

00:29:10.610 --> 00:29:11.520
's about this.

00:29:11.530 --> 00:29:13.520
And I think it's excellent and very important.

00:29:13.530 --> 00:29:15.520
And it makes the case.

00:29:15.530 --> 00:29:17.520
I do think that capitalism is compatible if you have a long

00:29:17.520 --> 00:29:20.010
enough time horizon and the right structural things, which I don

00:29:20.070 --> 00:29:21.510
't think we currently do.

00:29:21.530 --> 00:29:24.060
